Logistic Regression

Logistic regression is a statistical model to study the relationships between a set of qualitative variables x and a qualitative variable Y. It is a generalized linear model using a logistic function as a link function.

A logistic regression model thus allows us to predict the probability that an event will or will not occur based on the optimization of the regression coefficients. This result always varies between 0 and 1. When the predicted value is above a threshold, the event is likely to occur, while when the value is below the same threshold, it is not.

Logistic regression is frequently used in the social sciences because it allows us to reason in a ceteris paribus fashion. More precisely, the purpose of logistic regression is to isolate the effects of each variable, i.e.to identify the residual effects of an explanatory variable on a variable of interest, once the other explanatory variables introduced in the model have been taken into account. Logistic regression is thus used in credit scoring to identify the factors associated with default.

Ordinary logistic regression or binary logistic regression aims at explaining a binary variable of interest (i.e.default/non-default). The explanatory variables that will be introduced in the model can be quantitative or qualitative.

The most commonly used functions to link the probability p to the explanatory variables are the logistic function (known as the Logit model) and the distribution function of the standard normal distribution (known as the Probit model). These two functions are perfectly symmetrical and sigmoid. In our case, we will use a logistic model as a basic model.

If one or more qualitative explanatory variables have been selected, the results of the tests of equality of the parameters taken two by two of the different modalities of the qualitative variables are displayed. We thus introduce the term odds ratio, which allows us to analyze the impact of one modality of the variable compared to the modality used as a reference. Thus, a odds ratio equal to 1 means that there are no significant differences between the modality of the variable and its reference modality.

The strength of logistic regression lies in its simplicity, but especially in its interpretability. Indeed, the marginal effects are not directly readable, but the signs of the estimated coefficients are sufficient to determine the impact of a variable or a modality on the entire estimated model. This is why, by applying Ockhams razor principle, we may be tempted to select this model for our study. However, as explained above, logistic regression is only a linear model, and must therefore respect numerous hypotheses, including the absence of multicollinearity, which is not the case for our database.
